Your healthcare providers store lots of important information about your health.
A primary care provider is a healthcare professional who helps

• It looks at your health information\n• Checks if you match any study requirements\n• Suggests studies, clinical trials or programs that might help you

Health Match will look at things like:

• Your age and gender
• Health conditions
• Medications
• Lab and test results
• Device, wearable and other lifestyle details associated with your account

By joining Health Match, you\'re gaining access to personalized health insights and study recommendations based on your medical records. You have complete control to learn more about the study or program and decide which ones you want to join.

Health Match is a powerful feature in your Personal Health Record that allows you to have access to the latest clinical research and personalized health recommendations by using your consented health data to match you with relevant studies and programs.
Your privacy and data security are our top priority. You can update your preferences or opt-out at any time through your account settings.
We will notify you about updates to the latest research in your areas of interest
You\'ll receive notifications about matching opportunities via text, email or notifications.

You\'re now part of a community dedicated to advancing healthcare research and improving patient outcomes. Your participation helps connect you with potentially beneficial studies, clinical trials and programs based on your personal health information.

A urobilinogen in urine test measures the amount of urobilinogen in your urine (pee). Normal urine contains some urobilinogen. Too much urobilinogen in urine may be a sign of a liver disease, such as hepatitis or cirrhosis, or certain types of anemia.
